# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: aachen
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:aachen/1992-roermond-earthquake] The **1992 Roermond earthquake** occurred on 13 April, around 3:20 AM (1:20 UTC) with a moment magnitude of 5.3 and a maximum Mercalli intensity of VIII (*Severe*).
[src:aachen/1992-roermond-earthquake] Striking on the Peel Boundary Fault, a normal fault near Roermond, it was the strongest recorded earthquake in the Netherlands and in Northwestern Europe, and caused substantial damage to older buildings in the Netherlands and adjacent countries of Belgium and Germany.
[src:aachen/1992-roermond-earthquake] The city of Roermond lies above the Roer Graben, which forms the southeastern part of the Lower Rhine Graben (or Lower Rhine Embayment).
[src:aachen/1992-roermond-earthquake] These structures form part of the European Cenozoic Rift System, which formed within the foreland of the Alpine orogeny.
[src:aachen/1992-roermond-earthquake] The Roer graben formed during the Paleogene and is currently active as shown by the thickening of Quaternary sedimentary rocks into the basin.
[src:aachen/1992-roermond-earthquake] The graben is bounded by NW-SE trending normal fault systems, with the largest fault being the southwest-dipping Peel Boundary Fault, which displaces the base of the Quaternary sequence by about 175 m.
[src:aachen/1992-roermond-earthquake] All the major faults show evidence of neotectonics.
[src:aachen/1992-roermond-earthquake] The earthquake's focal mechanism showed almost pure normal faulting on a plane dipping southwest at 68°, identified as the Peel Boundary Fault.
[src:aachen/1992-roermond-earthquake] The epicentre of the earthquake lay kilometers away from the south of Roermond.
[src:aachen/1992-roermond-earthquake] The earthquake was recorded as 5.8 on the Richter scale (5.3 on the moment magnitude scale) and a maximum intensity of VIII (*Severe*) on the Mercalli intensity scale.
[src:aachen/1992-roermond-earthquake] An intensity of VIII means considerable damage to poorly built structures and heavy furniture is overturned.
[src:aachen/1992-roermond-earthquake] The earthquake was not evenly spread as some areas were hit harder than others.
[src:aachen/1992-roermond-earthquake] This earthquake could be felt as far away as the Czech Republic, Switzerland, France and England.
[src:aachen/1992-roermond-earthquake] In the regions between Roermond, Maaseik (Belgium), and Heinsberg (Germany), buildings, especially old buildings, and cars were destroyed.
[src:aachen/1992-roermond-earthquake] Two churches in Roermond, the Munsterkerk and Minderbroederskerk, were heavily damaged.
[src:aachen/1992-roermond-earthquake] The economic cost of the earthquake was estimated to be around 275 million guilders (around 125 million euros), of which 170 million guilders (around 77 million euros) of damage in the Netherlands.
[src:aachen/1992-roermond-earthquake] A 79-year-old woman died of a heart attack in Bonn.
[src:aachen/1992-roermond-earthquake] The earthquake was followed by more than 200 aftershocks.
[src:aachen/2006-fei-world-equestrian-games] The **2006 FEI World Equestrian Games** were held in Aachen, Germany from 20 August to 3 September 2006.
[src:aachen/2006-fei-world-equestrian-games] They were the 5th edition of the games which are held every four years and run by the FEI.
[src:aachen/2006-fei-world-equestrian-games] It was held in the Soers, a district of Aachen.
[src:aachen/2006-fei-world-equestrian-games] The main stadium of this event was the Hauptstadion.
[src:aachen/2006-fei-world-equestrian-games] On 18 September 2002 in Jerez de la Frontera, Spain, the FEI awarded the 2006 Games to Aachen.
[src:aachen/2006-fei-world-equestrian-games] The only other host city applicant was Lexington, Kentucky, United States (which was later awarded the following edition of the Games in 2010).
[src:aachen/2006-fei-world-equestrian-games] 16 events in 7 disciplines were held in Aachen.
[src:aachen/2006-fei-world-equestrian-games] 59 National Equestrian Federations sent athletes to the Aachen games.
[src:aachen/2019-european-heatwaves] In late June and late July 2019 there were two temporally distinct European heat waves, which set all-time high temperature records in Belgium, France, Germany, Luxembourg, the Netherlands, and the United Kingdom.
[src:aachen/2019-european-heatwaves] The first heat wave, in late June, killed over 567 people, and according to meteorologists it was caused by high pressure and winds from the Sahara Desert affecting large parts of the continent.
[src:aachen/2019-european-heatwaves] It resulted in record-breaking temperatures for the month of June at many locations.
[src:aachen/2019-european-heatwaves] France experienced temperatures in excess of 45 °C (113 °F) for the first time in recorded history.
[src:aachen/2019-european-heatwaves] A national all-time record high temperature of 46.0 °C (114.8 °F) occurred on 28 June in Vérargues.
[src:aachen/2019-european-heatwaves] In late July, a second heat wave occurred, during which all-time records were broken by 3 °C (5.4 °F) in Belgium, by 2.1 °C (3.8 °F) in Germany and the Netherlands, by 0.3 °C (0.5 °F) in Luxembourg, and by 0.2 °C (0.4 °F) in the United Kingdom.
[src:aachen/2019-european-heatwaves] The deaths of 868 people in France and one person in Belgium were reported, along with thousands of animals when ventilation systems in barns were overwhelmed.
[src:aachen/2019-european-heatwaves] The above-normal hot condition in June is caused by an anomalous long-lasting anticyclone in the upper troposphere, which advects warm air from the Sahel and Mediterranean region and enhances incoming solar radiation and surface turbulent fluxes.
[src:aachen/2019-european-heatwaves] The anomalous anticyclone results from an unusually-intensified British-Baikal Corridor pattern and a synoptic Rossby wave breaking event over Europe.
[src:aachen/2019-european-heatwaves] The July heat wave was caused by a strong omega block, consisting of hot, dry air from North Africa, trapped between cold storm systems.
[src:aachen/2019-european-heatwaves] The high-pressure area of hot air, called Yvonne, stretched from the central Mediterranean to Scandinavia and was pinned between two low-pressure areas, one over western Russia and the other over the eastern Atlantic.
[src:aachen/2019-european-heatwaves] Total excess deaths are estimated to be around 2,500 during the summer months in 2019.
[src:aachen/2019-european-heatwaves] Most of these were indirectly caused and were observed in statistical modeling later that year.
[src:aachen/2019-european-heatwaves] Based on individual country counts, that figure may be an under estimate.
[src:aachen/2019-european-heatwaves] The Dutch government reported 400 excess deaths in the week of the June heat wave, a figure comparable to those recorded during the 2006 European heat wave.
[src:aachen/2019-european-heatwaves] France estimated 1,435 additional deaths due to the heatwave.
[src:aachen/2019-european-heatwaves] Public Health England reported 900 excess deaths from the heatwave.
[src:aachen/2019-european-heatwaves] The Robert Koch institute reported 500 excess deaths in Berlin alone.
[src:aachen/2019-european-heatwaves] Belgium reported at least 716 excess deaths during the summer.
[src:aachen/2019-european-heatwaves] In June heat records were broken, on 30 June the temperature reached 38.5 °C (101.3 °F) in Innsbruck.
[src:aachen/2019-european-heatwaves] This was a heat record for June in Austria, and also the highest temperature measured during the heatwaves.
[src:aachen/2019-european-heatwaves] Belgium recorded three consecutive days exceeding 30 °C (86 °F); 25 June was the hottest day during this period, with many places exceeding 32 °C (90 °F) and other places nearly reaching 35 °C (95 °F).
[src:aachen/2019-european-heatwaves] During the period of hot weather, environmental officials warned of poor air quality levels, which would especially affect the young, elderly and people with respiratory illnesses.
[src:aachen/2019-european-heatwaves] It also affects small countries that rely on tourism as their main source of income.
[src:aachen/2019-european-heatwaves] On 24 July, the highest ever recorded temperature in Belgium was measured, reaching 40.2 °C (104.4 °F) in the town of Angleur, exceeding the previous record of 38.8 °C (101.8 °F), reached in 1947.
[src:aachen/2019-european-heatwaves] On the same day, passengers were evacuated from a Eurostar train that had broken down between Halle and Tubize, as many began to fall ill due to the extreme temperatures.
[src:aachen/2019-european-heatwaves] On 25 July, the national record was broken again, reaching 41.8 °C (107.2 °F) in Begijnendijk (Flemish Brabant).
[src:aachen/2019-european-heatwaves] The official KMI weather station in Uccle reported a maximum temperature of 39.7 °C (103.5 °F), while many other weather stations, some even close to the North Sea, reported temperatures in excess of 40.0 °C (104.0 °F).
[src:aachen/2019-european-heatwaves] The temperature record for June was recorded in Doksany and was 38.9 °C (102.0 °F).
[src:aachen/2019-european-heatwaves] High temperatures also complicated rail transport in the Czech Republic.
[src:aachen/2019-european-heatwaves] On 22 July 2019 the DMI issued a warning for high temperatures possibly up to 35 °C (95 °F).
[src:aachen/2019-european-heatwaves] On 24 July, the temperature reached 30.9 °C (87.6 °F) in Åbenrå, Svendborg and Nykøbing Falster.
[src:aachen/2019-european-heatwaves] On 25 July the temperature reached 32.0 °C (89.6 °F) in Vordingborg & Holbæk.
[src:aachen/2019-european-heatwaves] Temperatures for that day were forecasted up to 35 °C (95 °F), but due to afternoon thunderstorms the temperature only reached a maximum of 32.0 °C (89.6 °F).
[src:aachen/2019-european-heatwaves] On 28 July, Helsinki recorded a temperature of 33.2 °C (91.8 °F), breaking the city's previous record.
[src:aachen/2019-european-heatwaves] On the same day, 33.7 °C (92.7 °F) was recorded in Porvoo.
[src:aachen/2019-european-heatwaves] France was one of the most affected countries from the heatwave, with much of the country exceeding 32 °C (90 °F) on 26 June.
[src:aachen/2019-european-heatwaves] Météo France issued an Orange Alert for much of the country due to exceptionally hot temperatures, excluding coastal regions, e.g.
[src:aachen/2019-european-heatwaves] Brittany and the northern part of Hauts-de-France.
[src:aachen/2019-european-heatwaves] Four departments of France were put on Red Alert: Bouches-du-Rhône, Gard, Hérault and Vaucluse.
[src:aachen/2019-european-heatwaves] Owing to building codes with old structures common across the country, numerous buildings in France lack air conditioning.
[src:aachen/2019-european-heatwaves] The French Government acted more proactively for the heat wave in light of its failings during the 2003 European heat wave.
[src:aachen/2019-european-heatwaves] 15,000 people died during that event in France.
[src:aachen/2019-european-heatwaves] Approximately 4,000 schools closed nationwide.
[src:aachen/2019-european-heatwaves] Authorities in Paris opened public cooling rooms.
[src:aachen/2019-european-heatwaves] Parks and pools extended operation hours in multiple cities.
[src:aachen/2019-european-heatwaves] Museums with air conditioning allowed free entry for all people.
[src:aachen/2019-european-heatwaves] France observed temperatures in excess of 45 °C (113 °F) for the first time in recorded history.
[src:aachen/2019-european-heatwaves] A national all-time record of 46.0 °C (114.8 °F) was recorded by a staffed weather station in Vérargues on 28 June, verified by Météo France on 19 July.
[src:aachen/2019-european-heatwaves] Earlier, the highest temperature considered to have been reliably recorded during the heat wave was 45.9 °C (114.6 °F) by an automatic weather station in Gallargues-le-Montueux, also on 28 June.
[src:aachen/2019-european-heatwaves] These exceeded the previous record of 44.1 °C (111.4 °F), recorded in Conqueyrac and Saint-Christol-lès-Alès.
[src:aachen/2019-european-heatwaves] Twelve other locations observed temperatures above the previous record high.
[src:aachen/2019-european-heatwaves] Villevieille experienced temperatures of 45.1 °C (113.2 °F) on this day.
[src:aachen/2019-european-heatwaves] Numerous records were broken along the Mediterranean coastline.
[src:aachen/2019-european-heatwaves] Montpellier observed a temperature of 43.5 °C (110.3 °F), shattering the previous all-time by 5.8 °C (10.4 °F).
[src:aachen/2019-european-heatwaves] Nantes and Bourges saw their highest low-temperature ever during the overnight of 27–28 June at 24.7 °C (76.5 °F) and 23.8 °C (74.8 °F), respectively.
[src:aachen/2019-european-heatwaves] Five people died nationwide: four from drowning and one from heat stroke.
[src:aachen/2019-european-heatwaves] Police noted an increase in instances of illegal fire hydrant openings.
[src:aachen/2019-european-heatwaves] A six-year-old child was hospitalised in critical condition after being hit by a stream of water from an illegally opened hydrant.
[src:aachen/2019-european-heatwaves] Hospitals reported a significant increase in cases of cramps, dehydration, dizziness, and heart conditions.
[src:aachen/2019-european-heatwaves] In July 2019, France experienced its second heat wave in less than a month, beating several regional and national temperature records.
[src:aachen/2019-european-heatwaves] In the previous month, a national record temperature of 46.1 °C (115.0 °F) was measured in the southern commune of Gallargues-le-Montueux.
[src:aachen/2019-european-heatwaves] More than 50 French cities exceeded their previous high temperature records in this heat wave.
[src:aachen/2019-european-heatwaves] On 23 July 80 departments of France were included in an orange heat wave alert by Météo-France, and 20 departments were included in a red alert the next day.
[src:aachen/2019-european-heatwaves] On 24 July, a temperature of 41.2 °C (106.2 °F) was registered by Météo-France in Bordeaux, breaking the city's previous record of 40.7 °C (105.3 °F) in 2003.
[src:aachen/2019-european-heatwaves] Similarly, on 25 July, a temperature of 42.6 °C (108.7 °F) was recorded in Paris, also breaking the city's previous record of 40.4 °C (104.7 °F) in July 1947.
[src:aachen/2019-european-heatwaves] On the night of 24–25 July, France saw its hottest night since records began, as the whole country averaged an overnight low of 21.4 °C (70.5 °F), exceeding the record from the 2003 heat wave.
[src:aachen/2019-european-heatwaves] Lille also saw a high of 41.5 °C (106.7 °F) the following day, above the record of 37.6 °C (99.7 °F) that had been set the previous year.
[src:aachen/2019-european-heatwaves] On 25 July, the chief architect of the Notre-Dame de Paris cathedral told media that he feared that the heat wave could cause the cathedral's vaulted ceilings, damaged in an April 2019 fire, to collapse.
[src:aachen/2019-european-heatwaves] While he indicated the stone walls were still stable for the time being, he explained that the walls were still saturated with water sprayed by firefighters during the blaze, and rapid drying from the extreme temperatures could adversely affect the stability of the structure.
[src:aachen/2019-european-heatwaves] Two nuclear reactors in southwest France were shut down and the output of six reactors were curtailed to avoid breaching environmental limits on the temperature of the rivers they use for cooling water.
[src:aachen/2019-european-heatwaves] This reduced French nuclear power generation by around 5.2 gigawatts at a time of increased electricity demand due to the use of cooling devices.
[src:aachen/2019-european-heatwaves] According to the French Ministry of Health, 567 were reported to have died during the June heat wave, and 868 people died as a result of the July heat wave.
[src:aachen/2019-european-heatwaves] Most of Germany recorded temperatures exceeding 32 °C (90 °F) on 26 June as well as large parts of the country exceeding 35 °C (95 °F).
[src:aachen/2019-european-heatwaves] Temperatures as high as 37.5 °C (99.5 °F) were recorded in Berlin-Tempelhof, and Brandenburg had temperatures reaching 38.6 °C (101.5 °F), exceeding the previous June record of 38.2 °C (100.8 °F) recorded in Frankfurt.
[src:aachen/2019-european-heatwaves] Nationwide, the average temperature for all of June reached 19.8 °C (67.6 °F), marking the warmest June in 140 years of record-keeping.
[src:aachen/2019-european-heatwaves] Four people died from drowning nationwide.
[src:aachen/2019-european-heatwaves] On 25 July, a temperature of 42.6 °C (108.7 °F) was recorded in Lingen, Lower Saxony.
[src:aachen/2019-european-heatwaves] This beat the record for the highest ever temperature recorded in Germany, following its previous record of 40.5 °C (104.9 °F) measured a day earlier.
[src:aachen/2019-european-heatwaves] Twenty-five weather stations in the country reported temperatures of 40 °C (104 °F) or higher on 25 July.
[src:aachen/2019-european-heatwaves] Prior to this heat wave, the highest recorded temperature in Germany was 40.3 °C (104.5 °F) in Kitzingen in 2015.
[src:aachen/2019-european-heatwaves] At the end of the heat wave, on the evening of 26 July, a maximum purple alert for storms was issued for three districts (*Landkreise*) of the Land Baden-Württemberg, namely Freudenstadt, Böblingen and Calw.
[src:aachen/2019-european-heatwaves] After the heat wave ended in mainland Europe, the mass of warm air traveled north to Greenland, causing a heat wave that led to a melting of some 197 gigatonnes (217 billion short tons) of ice in July.
[src:aachen/2019-european-heatwaves] The melting was forecast to peak on 1 August.
[src:aachen/2019-european-heatwaves] For comparison, the entire melt season in 2012 caused 290 gigatonnes (320 billion short tons) of ice loss.
[src:aachen/2019-european-heatwaves] A record 56.5 percent of Greenland Ice Sheet was showing signs of melting on 31 July.
[src:aachen/2019-european-heatwaves] US National Snow and Ice Data Center estimated ice loss during the first week of August at 11–22 gigatonnes (12–24 billion short tons) per day with a total loss of 230 gigatonnes (250 billion short tons) for the melt season to date.
[src:aachen/2019-european-heatwaves] A wild fire which has been burning near Sisimiut since early July necessitated dispatching firefighters from Denmark, as the fire was endangering inhabited areas and had the potential to continue burning through the winter.
[src:aachen/2019-european-heatwaves] Forest fires are exceedingly rare in Greenland.
[src:aachen/2019-european-heatwaves] By 28 June, Italian authorities placed 16 cities under high alert for dangerous temperatures.
[src:aachen/2019-european-heatwaves] Civil security services distributed water to tourists visiting Rome.
[src:aachen/2019-european-heatwaves] A 72-year-old man died of heat stroke in the Milano Centrale railway station.
[src:aachen/2019-european-heatwaves] On 25 July, a red alert for extreme heat was put in place for the entire country by Meteolux.
[src:aachen/2019-european-heatwaves] The same day, a temperature of 40.8 °C (105.4 °F) was measured in Steinsel, the highest ever recorded in the country, beating the record of 40.5 °C (104.9 °F) set in Remich in 2003.
[src:aachen/2019-european-heatwaves] The high heat and dry conditions caused several fires during the heat wave.
[src:aachen/2019-european-heatwaves] On 24 July, a fire broke out near Schumannseck, and hay bales caught fire in a field.
[src:aachen/2019-european-heatwaves] On 25 July, a bush fire occurred in Hamm, and a fire truck exploded when it became engulfed in flames whilst attending the scene.
[src:aachen/2019-european-heatwaves] On 25 June, much of the inland areas of the Netherlands exceeded 32 °C (90 °F).
[src:aachen/2019-european-heatwaves] The KNMI issued a code yellow warning for large parts of the country due to the heat, and RIVM also put National Heat Plans into force in areas issued under code yellow.
[src:aachen/2019-european-heatwaves] De Bilt, where the headquarters of the KNMI is located, recorded a temperature of 33.2 °C (91.8 °F), and parts of Uden and Gelderland recorded temperatures as high as 36 °C (97 °F).
[src:aachen/2019-european-heatwaves] In July in the Netherlands, an orange alert was put in place for the entire country due to the extreme heat.
[src:aachen/2019-european-heatwaves] The previous high temperature heat record 38.6 °C (101.5 °F), set in Warnsveld in 1944, was broken on 24 July in Eindhoven (North Brabant) where the temperature reached 39.3 °C (102.7 °F).
[src:aachen/2019-european-heatwaves] The following day, 40.7 °C (105.3 °F) was measured in Gilze-Rijen (also North Brabant).
[src:aachen/2019-european-heatwaves] The West Frisian Islands was the only region for which no weather alert had been issued but there was a heatwave for the first time ever on Vlieland and Terschelling since measurements started in 1996.
[src:aachen/2019-european-heatwaves] On 27 July, the KNMI ended the orange alert for South Holland, Zeeland, North Brabant and Limburg.
[src:aachen/2019-european-heatwaves] The same day at 22:32 CEST they ended the orange alert for the whole country.
[src:aachen/2019-european-heatwaves] On 22 July, ProRail announced code red for traffic controllers, as extra alertness was necessary for disturbances on the tracks and other problems due to heat.
[src:aachen/2019-european-heatwaves] On 25 July, NS cancelled services on the Schiphol–Antwerp high-speed railway between Amsterdam—Schiphol— Rotterdam, and the connection between Amsterdam—Eindhoven and Eindhoven—Heerlen.
[src:aachen/2019-european-heatwaves] As trains were exposed to high temperatures, more maintenance was required and some were taken out of service.
[src:aachen/2019-european-heatwaves] Units without air conditioning or openable windows were also taken out of service.
[src:aachen/2019-european-heatwaves] This continued into the following day, except with four other routes made unavailable; Amsterdam—Alkmaar, Amsterdam—The Hague, Duivendrecht—Lelystad and Schiphol—Nijmegen.
[src:aachen/2019-european-heatwaves] Many farm animals died as a result of the high temperatures, mainly due to ventilation systems failing.
[src:aachen/2019-european-heatwaves] Due to a power failure in a chicken barn in Neer, 4,000 chickens died.
[src:aachen/2019-european-heatwaves] Hundreds of chickens also died whilst being transported to Poland on 24 July because of rising temperatures.
[src:aachen/2019-european-heatwaves] On the same day, hundreds of pigs died in Middelharnis because of power failure in ventilation systems, and 2,100 pigs died in Maarheeze as barns reached temperatures of 40 °C (104 °F).
[src:aachen/2019-european-heatwaves] Nearly 400 extra people were reported to have died during the heatwave compared to a regular summer week.
[src:aachen/2019-european-heatwaves] On 26 July, a temperature of 33.4 °C (92.1 °F) was recorded in Bergen Municipality in Norway, setting a new temperature record for the city.
[src:aachen/2019-european-heatwaves] A day later, at Laksfors railway station south of Mosjøen, a temperature of 35.6 °C (96.1 °F) was recorded, equalling the national all-time temperature record first set in June 1970.
[src:aachen/2019-european-heatwaves] However, the Norwegian Meteorological Institute later did not approve the recording due to too much gravel and too high vegetation near the station.
[src:aachen/2019-european-heatwaves] The highest recording approved was 35 °C (95 °F) at the Mosjøen Airport on 27 July, the warmest temperature ever recorded in Northern Norway and a tie with the all-time national high for July.
[src:aachen/2019-european-heatwaves] The same day, a temperature of 34.6 °C (94.3 °F) was recorded further north in Saltdal Municipality.
[src:aachen/2019-european-heatwaves] This is highest temperature ever recorded inside the Arctic Circle in Norway.
[src:aachen/2019-european-heatwaves] On 27 July, Trondheim Airport recorded a new all-time high with 33.5 °C (92.3 °F) and saw five consecutive days with high above 32 °C (90 °F).
[src:aachen/2019-european-heatwaves] The Norwegian Meteorological Institute said that it had recorded "tropical nights" in 20 locations in the south of the country, where temperatures stayed above 20 °C (68 °F) throughout the night.
[src:aachen/2019-european-heatwaves] Poland recorded high temperatures early in June, with much of the country exceeding 30 °C (86 °F) on 12 June.
[src:aachen/2019-european-heatwaves] Like much of Western and Central Europe, most of Poland recorded temperatures as high as 33 °C (91 °F) on 26 June.
[src:aachen/2019-european-heatwaves] Poland has also exceeded its previous June record, recording 38.2 °C (100.8 °F) in Radzyń.
[src:aachen/2019-european-heatwaves] Large parts of Spain recorded temperatures exceeding recorded 35 °C (95 °F) on 27 June, and recorded its hottest temperatures in the north east of the country, with temperatures reaching as high as 39.6 °C (103.3 °F) in Bilbao and exceeding 40 °C (104 °F) in Zaragoza on 27 June.
[src:aachen/2019-european-heatwaves] Zaragoza Airport registered 43.2 °C (109.8 °F) in June 2019, Zaragoza was forecasted to reach temperatures as high as 44 °C (111 °F), exceeding the June temperature record for the city.
[src:aachen/2019-european-heatwaves] At least two heat stroke deaths occurred in the country: a 93-year-old man in Valladolid and a 17-year-old boy in Córdoba.
[src:aachen/2019-european-heatwaves] A wildfire broke out in La Torre de l'Espanyol within the Province of Tarragona in Catalonia on 26 June.
[src:aachen/2019-european-heatwaves] According to local authorities, the fire ignited from decomposing chicken feces exposed to prolonged sunlight.
[src:aachen/2019-european-heatwaves] Strong winds caused the fire to expand, with the blaze covering 6,500 hectares (16,000 acres) by 28 June.
[src:aachen/2019-european-heatwaves] It was said to be the worst wildfire in Catalonia in 20 years.
[src:aachen/2019-european-heatwaves] By 28 June more than 600 firefighters and six aircraft were deployed to combat the blaze.
[src:aachen/2019-european-heatwaves] Dozens of people were displaced, including at least 30 in Flix.
[src:aachen/2019-european-heatwaves] Near the village, more than 200 sheep, 2 horses, and a donkey died in the fire.
[src:aachen/2019-european-heatwaves] One of Ascó's Nuclear Power Plant evacuation power lines was near the site the fire started, so it was subsequently switched off in an attempt to aid with the fire extinguishing tasks.
[src:aachen/2019-european-heatwaves] The plant continued to operate normally throughout the days.
[src:aachen/2019-european-heatwaves] Sweden was only affected in the southern portion of the country.
[src:aachen/2019-european-heatwaves] On 30 June Oskarshamn measured 33.7 °C (92.7 °F) the highest June temperature since 1970.
[src:aachen/2019-european-heatwaves] On 26 July, a temperature of 34.8 °C (94.6 °F) was recorded in Markusvinsa, the highest temperature recorded in the north of Sweden since 1945.
[src:aachen/2019-european-heatwaves] The Swedish Meteorological and Hydrological Institute issued a Class 1 heat warning for parts of the country, as well as a warning for potential water shortages in August in 15 counties.
[src:aachen/2019-european-heatwaves] To prevent forest fires due to the heat and dry weather, fire bans were put in place in several locations in Sweden.
[src:aachen/2019-european-heatwaves] A meteorologist at the institute stated that although above average, temperatures in the south of the country were not as extreme.
[src:aachen/2019-european-heatwaves] Mainly, the reason for this was that July started with a cool spell in Northern Europe in between the two heat waves.
[src:aachen/2019-european-heatwaves] In Switzerland, heat records were broken for the month of June at nearly 30 locations across the country.
[src:aachen/2019-european-heatwaves] Temperatures reached as high as 35.5 °C (95.9 °F) in Zürich and 35.3 °C (95.5 °F) in Basel on 26 June.
[src:aachen/2019-european-heatwaves] Areas with high altitudes also exceeded 30 °C (86 °F), with temperatures reaching as high as 30.3 °C (86.5 °F) in Col Des Mosses and Adelboden.
[src:aachen/2019-european-heatwaves] MeteoSwiss issued a Level 3 hazard due to high temperatures for much of the country, with large parts of Valais and Ticino under a Level 4 hazard, meaning high danger due to the exceptional heat.
[src:aachen/2019-european-heatwaves] The highest temperature measured during the heatwaves was 37.4 °C (99.3 °F) on 25 July in Basel.
[src:aachen/2019-european-heatwaves] On 29 June large parts of England, including the South and the Midlands, faced temperatures exceeding 30 °C (86 °F) with the highest temperature of 34.0 °C (93.2 °F) recorded at Heathrow Airport and RAF Northolt.
[src:aachen/2019-european-heatwaves] The heatwave was rather short lived in the United Kingdom, with temperatures dropping to near normal the next day.
[src:aachen/2019-european-heatwaves] One child drowned in the River Irwell in Greater Manchester after diving in to cool off during high temperatures.
[src:aachen/2019-european-heatwaves] On 23 July, Public Health England renewed a heat warning for the whole of the United Kingdom, urging people to "keep hydrated, find shade and take protection against the sun".
[src:aachen/2019-european-heatwaves] On the same night, widespread thunderstorms affected the country, with BBC Weather reporting around 48,000 lightning strikes overnight.
[src:aachen/2019-european-heatwaves] On 25 July, the Met Office announced that the United Kingdom had its hottest July day on record, with a temperature of 38.6 °C (101.5 °F) recorded in Rainham Kent.
[src:aachen/2019-european-heatwaves] This beat the previous July record of 36.7 °C (98.1 °F) in 2015, and marked the second time in history that the UK had recorded a temperature higher than 38.5 °C (101.3 °F).
[src:aachen/2019-european-heatwaves] On 29 July, sensors at the Cambridge University Botanic Garden recorded a temperature of 38.7 °C (101.7 °F) on 25 July, breaking the national all-time record of 38.5 °C (101.3 °F) set in Brogdale, Kent, on 10 August 2003.
[src:aachen/2019-european-heatwaves] Brogdale broke the highest temperature recorded in SE England for July with 38.4 °C (101.1 °F), 0.1 °C off its previous record in 2003.
[src:aachen/2019-european-heatwaves] New local temperature records were set in towns and cities across the country on 25 July, including 31.6 °C (88.9 °F) in Edinburgh and 35.1 °C (95.2 °F) in Sheffield.
[src:aachen/2019-european-heatwaves] On 25 July, Network Rail began to impose speed restrictions across its network to reduce buckling rails, as track temperatures surpassed 50 °C (122 °F).
[src:aachen/2019-european-heatwaves] Measures included painting railway tracks white to reduce the temperature of the steel, and cancelling services.
[src:aachen/2019-european-heatwaves] East Midlands Trains, Southeastern and Greater Anglia advised passengers against all but essential travel.
[src:aachen/2019-european-heatwaves] Many heat-related incidents on the country's rail network caused widespread disruptions, especially affecting intercity services from London.
[src:aachen/2019-european-heatwaves] Damage to overhead line equipment occurred in Peterborough, Handsworth and Camden, as well as a trackside grass fire caused by cables snapping near West Hampstead.
[src:aachen/2019-european-heatwaves] Trains arriving and departing from Birmingham New Street and around the West Midlands were also disrupted.
[src:aachen/2019-european-heatwaves] Passengers were advised not to start new journeys as the overheating of overhead cables rendered many services unable to run.
[src:aachen/2019-european-heatwaves] On 26 July, all but essential travel had been advised against, after the extreme heat and storms caused severe disruption to the rail network and airports.
[src:aachen/2019-european-heatwaves] Thameslink ran reduced services, with half of its lines unavailable.
[src:aachen/2019-european-heatwaves] East Midlands Trains services between Sheffield, Nottingham, Derby and London St Pancras were disrupted due to overhead wire damage from the heat of the previous day, and an emergency timetable was put in place.
[src:aachen/2019-european-heatwaves] All Eurostar services to and from Paris were suspended for an "undetermined amount of time" due to an exploded cable, as well as delays lasting up to an hour on Brussels services.
[src:aachen/2019-european-heatwaves] Several flights were cancelled and delayed from Heathrow, Gatwick and London City airports due to "extreme weather conditions across Europe".
[src:aachen/2019-european-heatwaves] A spokesperson from Heathrow said that flights had been affected by overnight storms as a result of the heat.
[src:aachen/2019-european-heatwaves] As of 1 August, the World Meteorological Organisation considered July 2019 to be at least tied for the hottest month ever recorded, based on global average temperature.
[src:aachen/2019-european-heatwaves] Previously, June 2019 was found to be the hottest June on record.
[src:aachen/2019-european-heatwaves] This was confirmed on 5 August by EU Earth Observation Network, which found it 0.04 °C (0.072 °F) hotter than the previous record-holder, July 2016.
[src:aachen/2019-european-heatwaves] 2019 on the whole was found to be on track for the new hottest year on record.
[src:aachen/2019-european-heatwaves] A study of the event, a collaboration between several European climatological organisations and institutes, was published on 2 August 2019.
[src:aachen/2019-european-heatwaves] It found that the temperatures experienced during the heat wave would have been 1.5 to 3 °C (2.7 to 5.4 °F) lower had it not been for anthropogenic global warming, and that temperatures recorded in France and Netherlands would have occurred there on average less than once a millennium.
[src:aachen/2019-european-heatwaves] According to the study's lead author, at the current pace of warming, such heatwaves will be another 3 °C (5.4 °F) stronger by 2050.
[src:aachen/274835-aachen-p01] The following is a partial list of minor planets, running from minor-planet number 274001 through 275000, inclusive.
[src:aachen/274835-aachen-p01] The primary data for this and other partial lists is based on JPL's "Small-Body Orbital Elements" and data available from the Minor Planet Center.
[src:aachen/274835-aachen-p01] Critical list information is also provided by the MPC, unless otherwise specified from Lowell Observatory.
[src:aachen/274835-aachen-p01] A detailed description of the table's columns and additional sources are given on the main page including a complete list of every page in this series, and a statistical break-up on the dynamical classification of minor planets.
[src:aachen/274835-aachen-p01] Also see the summary list of all named bodies in numerical and alphabetical order, and the corresponding naming citations for the number range of this particular list.
[src:aachen/274835-aachen-p01] New namings may only be added to this list after official publication, as the preannouncement of names is condemned by the Working Group for Small Bodies Nomenclature of the International Astronomical Union.
[src:aachen/aachen-district] The district of **Aachen** (German: *Städteregion Aachen*) is a district in the west of North Rhine-Westphalia, Germany.
[src:aachen/aachen-district] Neighboring districts are Heinsberg, Düren, Euskirchen, and also the Netherlands province of Limburg and the Belgian province of Liège.
[src:aachen/aachen-district] Its administrative body is the *Städteregionsparlament* ("regional parliament"), headed by the *Städteregionspräsident* or "region president" (Tim Grüttemeier (CDU) since 2019).
[src:aachen/aachen-district] As of 21 October 2009, the *Städteregion Aachen* (literally: "cities region" Aachen) was formed from the former district Aachen (*Kreis Aachen*) and the city of Aachen.
[src:aachen/aachen-district] This is the first *Städteregion* that was formed in North Rhine-Westphalia.
[src:aachen/aachen-district] Its status is similar to that of the district Hanover (*Region Hannover*) in Lower Saxony, in that the powers of the city of Aachen are slightly less than those of a district-free city (*Kreisfreie Stadt*).
[src:aachen/aachen-district] The *Landkreis Aachen* was formed in 1816 from the two French cantons Burtscheid and Eschweiler, with its capital set to the city of Burtscheid.
[src:aachen/aachen-district] In 1897 Burtscheid was incorporated into the city of Aachen, but the administrative seat stayed there, even though the capital was no longer part of the district.
[src:aachen/aachen-district] The Aachen district was re-formed in 1972, and part of it was incorporated to the district-free city of Aachen.
[src:aachen/aachen-district] At that point in time, the policy that no independent large city in North Rhine-Westphalia should be the seat of its district was not yet in effect.
[src:aachen/aachen-district] In the larger independent cities of Bielefeld (1973) and Münster (1975), the districts named after them were consistently dissolved and several of their communities were incorporated into the respective large city.
[src:aachen/aachen-district] In the case of Aachen, however, no further municipal reform was carried out and the separation of city and district remained.
[src:aachen/aachen-district] In 1975 this district of Aachen was merged with the district of Monschau, and parts of the districts of Düren, Jülich, Schleiden and Selfkant.
[src:aachen/aachen-district] In 2004, a special-purpose association was formed including the city of Aachen, the district of Aachen, and the nine municipalities belonging to the district.
[src:aachen/aachen-district] Its regular meetings consisted of 60 representatives of the association members with voting rights, and focused on expanding cooperation between the members, road traffic management, school administration, and economic development.
[src:aachen/aachen-district] This was a predecessor to the 2009 *Städteregion*.
[src:aachen/aachen-district] In 2009, the North Rhine-Westphalia state parliament reorganized the district to include the city of Aachen, modeled after the district of Hanover.
[src:aachen/aachen-district] The existing Aachen district was dissolved and the new *Städteregion Aachen* took over tasks such as traffic planning and emergency services from the cities within it.
[src:aachen/aachen-district] Geographically the district covers a part of the Eifel mountains in the south, but also the lowlands of the Lower Rhine Bay.
[src:aachen/aachen-district] Parts of the Aachen district belong to the Eifel National Park.
[src:aachen/aachen-district] Most important rivers within the Aachen district are the Roer and its tributaries Wurm and Inde.
[src:aachen/aachen-district] It borders also to the Rursee (Roer Reservoir) and the Obersee (upper Roer Reservoir).
[src:aachen/aachen-district] The top of the coat of arms shows the black lion, the sign of Jülich, as the district contains mostly former parts of the duchy of Jülich.
[src:aachen/aachen-district] In the bottom the swan on a deer antler is the sign of the city of Burtscheid, which was the capital of the *Landkreis Aachen* until 1897, when it was incorporated into the city of Aachen.
[src:aachen/aachen-mitte] As the center of the city of Aachen, the district is by far the most populated, with over 168,000 residents.
[src:aachen/aachen-mitte] It contains both the Aachen Cathedral and Aachen Rathaus, which are each near the city center, as well as Aachen's main theatre.
[src:aachen/aachen-mitte] Numerous squares, including Hansemannplatz, Kaiserplatz, and Lindenplatz are likewise contained within the district, as is the medieval *Ponttor*, which was one of the original gates in the wall surrounding the city.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] The once Celtic settlement was equipped with several *thermae* in the course of colonization by Roman pioneers settling at the warm Aachen thermal springs around the 1st century.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] After the withdrawal of the Roman troops, the vicus *Aquae Granni* was Frankized around the 5th century, by which it came under Merovingian and later Carolingian rule.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] With the completion of the Carolingian Palace of Aachen at the transition to the 9th century, Aachen was constituted as the main royal residence of the Frankish Empire ruled by Charlemagne.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] Because of that, the city is sometimes called the "cradle of Europe".
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] After the Treaty of Verdun, the city was within the borders of Middle Francia, until it became part of East Francia after the Treaty of Meerssen (870).
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] It subsequently was part of the Holy Roman Empire and was granted city rights in 1166 by Emperor Frederick Barbarossa, becoming an imperial city.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] It served as the coronation site where 31 Holy Roman Emperors were crowned Kings of the Germans from 936 to 1531, until Frankfurt became the preferred place of coronation.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] One of Germany's leading institutes of higher education in technology, the RWTH Aachen University *(Rheinisch-Westfälisch Technische Hochschule Aachen)*, is located in the city.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] Its university hospital Uniklinikum Aachen is Europe's largest single-building hospital.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] Aachen's industries include science, engineering and information technology.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] In 2009, Aachen was ranked eighth among cities in Germany for innovation.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] Aachen is located at the northern foothills of the High Fens and the Eifel Mountains.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] It sits on the Wurm River, a tributary of the Rur, and together with Mönchengladbach, it is the only larger German city in the drainage basin of the Meuse.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] The regional dialect spoken in the city is a Central Franconian, Ripuarian variant with strong Limburgish influences from the dialects in the neighbouring Netherlands.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] As a Rhenish city, Aachen is one of the main centres of carnival celebrations in Germany, along with Cologne and Mainz.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] The culinary specialty for which the city is best known is Aachener Printen, a type of gingerbread.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] The name *Aachen* is a modern descendant, like southern German *Ach(e)*, German: *Aach*, meaning "river" or "stream", from Old High German *ahha*, meaning "water" or "stream", which directly translates (and etymologically corresponds) to Latin *Aquae*, referring to the springs.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] The location has been inhabited by humans since the Neolithic era, about 5,000 years ago, attracted to its warm mineral springs.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] Latin *Aquae* figures in Aachen's Roman name *Aquae granni*, which meant "waters of Grannus", referring to the Celtic god of healing who was worshipped at the springs.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] This word became *Åxhe* in Walloon and *Aix* in French, and subsequently *Aix-la-Chapelle* to distinguish it from Aix-en-Provence, after Charlemagne had his palatine chapel built there in the late 8th century and then made the city his empire's capital.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] Flint quarries on the Lousberg, Schneeberg, and Königshügel, first used during Neolithic times (3000–2500 BC), attest to the long occupation of the site of Aachen, as do recent finds under the modern city's *Elisengarten* pointing to a former settlement from the same period.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] Bronze Age (around 1600 BC) settlement is evidenced by the remains of barrows (burial mounds) found, for example, on the Klausberg.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] During the Iron Age, the area was settled by Celtic peoples who were perhaps drawn by the marshy Aachen basin's hot sulphur springs where they worshipped Grannus, god of light and healing.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] Proofs of a Celts settlements on Aachens territories at the beginning of the Gallic War do not exist at the moment.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] The 25-hectare Roman spa resort town of Aquae Granni was, according to legend, founded by Grenus, under Hadrian, around 124 AD.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] Grenus refers to the Celtic god, and it seems it was the Roman 6th Legion at the start of the 1st century AD that first channelled the hot springs into a spa at Büchel, adding at the end of the same century the *Münstertherme* spa, two water pipelines, and a probable sanctuary dedicated to Grannus.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] A kind of forum, surrounded by colonnades, connected the two spa complexes.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] There was an extensive residential area.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] The Romans built bathhouses near Burtscheid.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] A temple precinct called *Vernenum* was built near the modern Kornelimünster/Walheim.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] Today, remains have been found of three bathhouses, including two fountains in the *Elisenbrunnen* and the Burtscheid bathhouse.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] Roman civil administration in Aachen eventually broke down as the baths and other public buildings (along with most of the villae rusticae of the surrounding countryside) were destroyed around AD 375 at the start of the migration period.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] The last Roman coin finds are from the time of Emperor Gratian (AD 375–383).
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] Rome withdrew its troops from the area, but the town remained populated.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] By 470, the town came to be ruled by the Ripuarian Franks and subordinated to their capital, Cologne.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] During the Roman period, Aachen was the site of a flourishing Jewish community.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] Pepin the Short had a castle residence built in the town, due to the proximity of the hot springs and also for strategic reasons as it is located between the Rhineland and northern France.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] In the year of his coronation as king of the Franks, 768, Charlemagne came to spend Christmas at Aachen for the first time.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] He remained there in a mansion which he may have extended, although there is no source attesting to any significant building activity at Aachen in his time, apart from the building of the Palatine Chapel (since 1930, cathedral) and the Palace.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] Charlemagne spent most winters in Aachen between 792 and his death in 814.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] Aachen became the focus of his court and the political centre of his empire.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] During the Carolingian empire, a Jewish community lived near the royal palace.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] In Jewish texts, the city of Aachen was called *Aish* or *Ash* (אש).
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] In 797, Isaac, a Jewish merchant, accompanied two ambassadors of Charlemagne to the court of Harun al-Rashid.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] He returned to Aachen in July 802, bearing an elephant called Abul-Abbas as a gift for the emperor.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] By the terms of the Treaty of Verdun 834, Aachen became part of Middle Francia, governed by emperor Lothair.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] He was succeeded by Lothair II as king of Lotharingia by the terms of the Treaty of Prüm.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] By the Treaty of Meerssen 870, Aachen came to East Francia.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] Within East Francia, later the Holy Roman Empire until 1166, Aachen was part of the Duchy of Lower Lotharingia.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] In 936, Otto I was crowned king of East Francia in the collegiate church built by Charlemagne.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] During the reign of Otto II, the nobles revolted and the West Franks under Lothair raided Aachen in 978.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] Aachen was attacked again by Odo of Champagne, who attacked the imperial palace while Conrad II was absent.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] Odo relinquished it and was killed afterwards.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] The palace and town of Aachen had fortifying walls built by order of Emperor Frederick Barbarossa between 1172 and 1176.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] Over the next 500 years, most kings of Germany who ruled the Holy Roman Empire were crowned in Aachen.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] The original audience hall built by Charlemagne was torn down and replaced by the current city hall in 1330.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] During the 13th century, many Jews converted to Christianity, as shown in the records of the Aachen Minster (today's Cathedral).
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] In 1486, the Jews of Aachen offered gifts to Maximilian I during his coronation ceremony.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] The last king to be crowned here was Ferdinand I in 1531.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] During the Middle Ages, Aachen remained a city of regional importance, due to its proximity to Flanders; it achieved a modest position in the trade in woollen cloths, favoured by imperial privilege.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] The city remained a free imperial city, subject to the emperor only, but was politically far too weak to influence the policies of any of its neighbours.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] The only dominion it had was over Burtscheid, a neighbouring territory ruled by a Benedictine abbess, which was forced to accept that all of its traffic must pass through the "Aachener Reich".
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] As an imperial city, Aachen held certain political privileges that allowed it to remain independent of the troubles of Europe for many years.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] It remained a direct vassal of the Holy Roman Empire throughout most of the Middle Ages.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] It was also the site of many important church councils, including the Council of 837 and the Council of 1166, a council convened by the antipope Paschal III.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] Parts of Aachen belonged to Imperial Abbey of Burtscheid, Reichsabtei Kornelimünster, Duchy of Juelich and the Duchy of Limburg.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] Aachen was an important site for the production of historical manuscripts.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] Under Charlemagne's purview, both the Ada Gospels and the Coronation Gospels may have been produced in Aachen.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] In addition, quantities of the other texts in the court library were also produced locally.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] During the reign of Louis the Pious (814–840), substantial quantities of ancient texts were produced at Aachen, including legal manuscripts such as the leges scriptorium group, patristic texts including the five manuscripts of the Bamberg Pliny Group.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] Finally, under Lothair I (840–855), texts of outstanding quality were still being produced.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] This however marked the end of the period of manuscript production at Aachen.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] In 1598, following the invasion of Spanish troops from the Netherlands, Rudolf deposed all Protestant office holders in Aachen and went as far as expelling them from the city.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] From the early 16th century, Aachen started to lose its power and influence.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] First the coronations of emperors were moved from Aachen to Frankfurt.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] 1614 Aachen became theatre of the Siege of Aachen (1614) within the War of the Jülich Succession.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] Although religious changes were forced several times in Aachen and Protestant communities were banned, hardly any fighting took place during the Thirty Years' War.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] The religious wars had been followed by the great fire of 1656.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] After the destruction of most of the city in 1656, the rebuilding was mostly in the Baroque style.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] The decline of Aachen culminated in 1794, when the French, led by General Charles Dumouriez, occupied Aachen..
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] The area of Aachen had been scene of battles within the Flanders Campaign in autumn 1794: Battle of Ourthe, Battle of Aldenhoven, Siege of Maastricht.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] In 1542, the Dutch humanist and physician Francis Fabricius published his study of the health benefits of the hot springs in Aachen.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] By the middle of the 17th century, the city had developed a considerable reputation as a spa, although this was in part because Aachen was then – and remained well into the 19th and early 20th century – a place of high-level prostitution.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] Traces of this hidden agenda of the city's history are found in the 18th-century guidebooks to Aachen as well as to the other spas.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] The main indication for visiting patients, ironically, was syphilis; only by the end of the 19th century had rheumatism become the most important object of cures at Aachen and Burtscheid.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] Aachen was chosen as the site of several important congresses and peace treaties: the first congress of Aachen (often referred to as the Congress of Aix-la-Chapelle in English) on 2 May 1668, leading to the First Treaty of Aachen in the same year which ended the War of Devolution.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] The second congress ended with the second treaty in 1748, ending the War of the Austrian Succession.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] In 1789, there was a constitutional crisis in the Aachen government, and in 1794 Aachen lost its status as a free imperial city.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] In 1629, the Aachen Jewish community was expelled from the city.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] In 1667, six Jews were allowed to return.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] Most of the Aachen Jewish community settled in Burtscheid.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] As recently as the late 18th century the Abbess of Burtscheid was still prevented from building a road linking her territory to the neighbouring estates of the duke of Jülich; the city of Aachen deployed its handful of soldiers to chase away road-diggers.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] On 9 February 1801, the Peace of Lunéville removed the ownership of Aachen and the entire "left bank" of the Rhine from Germany (the Holy Roman Empire) and granted it to France.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] In 1815, control of the town was passed to the Kingdom of Prussia through an agreement reached by the Congress of Vienna.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] The third congress took place in 1818, to decide the fate of occupied Napoleonic France.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] The current territory of Aachen belonged entirely to the Arrondissement d'Aix-la-Chapelle.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] In 1815, after the Second Treaty of Paris, finishing the Napoleonic Wars, the Kingdom of Prussia took over within the new German Confederation.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] The city was one of its most socially and politically backward centres until the end of the 19th century.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] The Kingdom of Prussia created the "Regierungsbezirk Aachen" (governmental district) and integrated it into the Prussian province Grand Duchy of the Lower Rhine, from 1822 the Rhine Province.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] Starting in 1838, the railway from Cologne to Belgium passed through Aachen.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] By "Gesetz betreffend die Vereinigung der Stadtgemeinde Burtscheid mit der Stadtgemeinde Aachen vom 29.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] März 1897 nebst Vertrag" Aachen and Burtscheid merged 1897.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] The city suffered extreme overcrowding and deplorable sanitary conditions until 1875, when the medieval fortifications were abandoned as a limit to building and new, better housing was built in the east of the city, where sanitary drainage was easiest.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] In December 1880, the Aachen tramway network was opened, and in 1895 it was electrified.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] In the 19th century and up to the 1930s, the city was important in the production of railway locomotives and carriages, iron, pins, needles, buttons, tobacco, woollen goods, and silk goods.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] Aachen was enlarged 1 April 1906 by "Gesetz betreffend die Vereinigung der Gemeinde Forst mit der Stadtgemeinde Aachen vom 31.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] März 1906 nebst Vertrag" by incorporation of Forst.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] The Belgium Campaign within World War I started in Aachen.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] After World War I, Aachen was occupied by the Entente until 1930, along with the rest of German territory west of the Rhine.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] Aachen was one of the locations involved in the Rhenish Republic.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] On 21 October 1923, an armed mob took over the city hall.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] Similar actions took place in Mönchengladbach, Duisburg, and Krefeld.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] During the interwar period, Aachen was assigned some areas of the former district of Eupen.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] Also the Western Campaign of World War II started nearby Aachen with the Battle of Maastricht.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] Aachen was heavily damaged during World War II.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] Blood mentioned more than 120 air strikes on Aachen between 1940 an 1944.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] According to Jörg Friedrich in *The Fire* (2002), two Allied air raids on 11 April and 24 May 1944 "radically destroyed" the city.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] The first killed 1,525, including 212 children, and bombed six hospitals.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] During the second, 442 aircraft hit two railway stations, killed 207, and left 15,000 homeless.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] The raids destroyed Aachen-Eilendorf and Aachen-Burtscheid.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] In autumn 1944 Aachen and its surroundings were reached by the Western Allied Siegfried Line campaign.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] The city and its fortified surroundings were besieged from 12 September to 21 October 1944 by the US 1st Infantry Division with the 3rd Armored Division assisting from the south.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] Around 13 October the US 2nd Armored Division, coming from the north, and got as close as Würselen, while the 30th Infantry Division completed the encirclement of Aachen on 16 October 1944.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] With reinforcements from the US 28th Infantry Division the battle continued involving direct assaults through the heavily defended city, which forced the German garrison to surrender on 21 October 1944.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] Aachen was the first German city to be captured by the Western Allies, and its residents welcomed the soldiers as liberators.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] What remained of the city was destroyed—in some areas completely—during the fighting, mostly by American artillery fire and demolitions carried out by the Waffen-SS defenders.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] Damaged buildings included medieval churches and the Rathaus (city hall), although Aachen Cathedral was largely unscathed.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] 4,000 inhabitants remained in the city; the rest had followed evacuation orders.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] Its first Allied-appointed mayor, Franz Oppenhoff, was assassinated by an SS commando unit.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] On 16 May 1815, the Jewish community of the city offered an homage in its synagogue to the Prussian king, Friedrich Wilhelm III.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] In 1862, a large synagogue was built, later called the Old Synagogue.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] On *Kristallnacht* in 1938, the synagogue was destroyed.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] By the onset of World War II in 1939, many Jews had emigrated or were arrested, and only 782 remained in the city.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] At the end of the war in 1945, only 62 Jews lived in the city.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] As of 2003, 1,434 Jews were again living in Aachen.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] Subsequent the German surrender finishing the Battle of Aachen 21 October 1944, the Supreme Headquarters Allied Expeditionary Force acted as military government.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] Aachen within the northern part of Rhine Province became part of British occupation zone in Germany.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] Aachen also belonged to the British zone under Belgian control.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] 46, British Military Government created the "Land Nordrhein/Westfalen", including the "Regierungsbezirk Aachen", 23 August 1946.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] 23 May 1949 Aachen became part of the Federal Republic of Germany.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] With the Aachen Law of 1971, Aachen was merged with Kornelimünster, Brand, Walheim, Laurensberg, Richterich, Haaren, Eilendorf.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] After the abolition of the Aachen governmental district, August 1972, Aachen became part of the Cologne governmental district.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] Aachen is located in the middle of the Meuse–Rhine Euroregion, close to the border tripoint of Germany, the Netherlands, and Belgium.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] The town of Vaals in the Netherlands lies nearby at about 6 km (4 mi) from Aachen's city centre, while the Dutch city of Heerlen and Eupen, the capital of the German-speaking Community of Belgium, are both located about 20 km (12 mi) from Aachen city centre.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] Aachen lies near the head of the open valley of the Wurm (which today flows through the city in canalised form), part of the larger basin of the Meuse, and about 30 km (19 mi) north of the High Fens, which form the northern edge of the Eifel uplands of the Rhenish Massif.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] The maximum dimensions of the city's territory are 21.6 km (13+3⁄8 mi) from north to south, and 17.2 km (10+3⁄4 mi) from east to west.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] The highest point in Aachen, located in the far southeast of the city, lies at an elevation of 410 m (1,350 ft) above sea level.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] The lowest point, in the north, and on the border with the Netherlands, is at 125 m (410 ft).
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] As the westernmost city in Germany (and close to the Low Countries), Aachen and the surrounding area belongs to a temperate climate zone (Cfb), with humid weather, mild winters, and warm summers.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] Because of its location north of the Eifel and the High Fens and its subsequent prevailing westerly weather patterns, rainfall in Aachen (on average 805 mm/year) is comparatively higher than, for example, in Bonn (with 669 mm/year).
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] Another factor in the local weather forces of Aachen is the occurrence of Foehn winds on the southerly air currents, which results from the city's geographic location on the northern edge of the Eifel.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] Because the city is surrounded by hills, it suffers from inversion-related smog.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] Some areas of the city have become urban heat islands as a result of poor heat exchange, both because of the area's natural geography and from human activity.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] The city's numerous cold air corridors, which are slated to remain as free as possible from new construction, therefore play an important role in the urban climate of Aachen.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] The January average is 3.0 °C (37 °F), while the July average is 18.5 °C (65 °F).
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] Precipitation is almost evenly spread throughout the year.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] In the 1991–2020 period, the record latest freeze (at 2 m above ground) of spring occurred on 28 April and the record first fall freeze on 13 October.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] The geology of Aachen is very structurally heterogeneous.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] The oldest occurring rocks in the area surrounding the city originate from the Devonian period and include carboniferous sandstone, greywacke, claystone and limestone.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] These formations are part of the Rhenish Massif, north of the High Fens.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] In the Pennsylvanian subperiod of the Carboniferous geological period, these rock layers were narrowed and folded as a result of the Variscan orogeny.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] After this event, and over the course of the following 200 million years, this area has been continuously flattened.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] During the Cretaceous period, the ocean penetrated the continent from the direction of the North Sea up to the mountainous area near Aachen, bringing with it clay, sand, and chalk deposits.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] While the clay (which was the basis for a major pottery industry in nearby Raeren) is mostly found in the lower areas of Aachen, the hills of the Aachen Forest and the Lousberg were formed from upper Cretaceous sand and chalk deposits.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] More recent sedimentation is mainly located in the north and east of Aachen and was formed through Tertiary and Quaternary river and wind activities.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] Along the major thrust fault of the Variscan orogeny, there are over 30 thermal springs in Aachen and Burtscheid.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] At the end of 2009, the foreign-born residents of Aachen made up 13.6 percent of the total population.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] A significant portion of foreign residents are students at the RWTH Aachen University.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] Aachen is at the western end of the Benrath line that divides High German to the south from the rest of the West Germanic speech area to the north.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] Aachen's local dialect is called *Öcher Platt* and belongs to Ripuarian.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] The city is divided into seven administrative districts, or boroughs, each with its own district council, district leader, and district authority.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] The councils are elected locally by those who live within the district, and these districts are further subdivided into smaller sections for statistical purposes, with each sub-district named by a two-digit number.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] The current mayor of Aachen is Michael Ziemons of the CDU, who was elected in 2025.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] The Aachen city council governs the city alongside the mayor.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] Aachen Cathedral was erected on the orders of Charlemagne.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] Construction began *c.* AD 796, and it was, on completion *c.* 798, the largest cathedral north of the Alps.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] It was modelled after the Basilica of San Vitale, in Ravenna, Italy, and was built by Odo of Metz.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] Charlemagne also desired for the chapel to compete with the Lateran Palace, both in quality and authority.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] It was originally built in the Carolingian style, including marble covered walls, and mosaic inlay on the dome.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] On his death, Charlemagne's remains were interred in the cathedral and can be seen there to this day.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] The cathedral was extended several times in later ages, turning it into a curious and unique mixture of building styles.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] The throne and gallery portion date from the Ottonian, with portions of the original opus sectile floor still visible.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] The 13th century saw gables being added to the roof, and after the fire of 1656, the dome was rebuilt.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] Finally, a choir was added around the start of the 15th century.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] After Frederick Barbarossa canonised Charlemagne in 1165 the chapel became a destination for pilgrims.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] For 600 years, from 936 to 1531, Aachen Cathedral was the church of coronation for 30 German kings and 12 queens.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] The church built by Charlemagne is still the main attraction of the city.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] In addition to holding the remains of its founder, it became the burial place of his successor Otto III.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] In the upper chamber of the gallery, Charlemagne's marble throne is housed.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] Aachen Cathedral has been designated as a UNESCO World Heritage Site.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] Most of the marble and columns used in the construction of the cathedral were brought from Rome and Ravenna, including the sarcophagus in which Charlemagne was eventually laid to rest.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] A bronze bear from Gaul was placed inside, along with an equestrian statue from Ravenna, believed to be Theodric, in contrast to a wolf and a statue of Marcus Aurelius in the Capitoline.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] Bronze pieces such as the doors and railings, some of which have survived to present day, were cast in a local foundry.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] Finally, there is uncertainty surrounding the bronze pine cone in the chapel, and where it was created.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] Wherever it was made, it was also a parallel to a piece in Rome, this in Old St.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] Aachen Cathedral Treasury has housed, throughout its history, a collection of liturgical objects.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] The origin of this church treasure is in dispute as some say Charlemagne himself endowed his chapel with the original collection, while the rest were collected over time.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] Others say all of the objects were collected over time, from such places as Jerusalem and Constantinople.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] The location of this treasury has moved over time and was unknown until the 15th century when it was located in the Matthiaskapelle (St.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] Matthew's Chapel) until 1873, when it was moved to the Karlskapelle (Charles' Chapel).
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] From there it was moved to the Hungarian Chapel in 1881 and in 1931 to its present location next to the Allerseelenkapelle (Poor Souls' Chapel).
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] Only six of the original Carolingian objects have remained, and of those only three are left in Aachen: the Aachen Gospels, a diptych of Christ, and an early Byzantine silk.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] The Coronation Gospels and a reliquary burse of St.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] Stephen were moved to Vienna in 1798 and the Talisman of Charlemagne was given as a gift in 1804 to Josephine Bonaparte and subsequently to Rheims Cathedral.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] 210 documented pieces have been added to the treasury since its inception, typically to receive in return legitimisation of linkage to the heritage of Charlemagne.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] The Lothar Cross, the Gospels of Otto III and multiple additional Byzantine silks were donated by Otto III.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] Part of the Pala d'Oro and a covering for the Aachen Gospels were made of gold donated by Henry II.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] Frederick Barbarossa donated the candelabrum that adorns the dome and also once "crowned" the Shrine of Charlemagne, which was placed underneath in 1215.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] Charles IV donated a pair of reliquaries.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] Louis XI gave, in 1475, the crown of Margaret of York, and, in 1481, another arm reliquary of Charlemagne.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] Maximilian I and Charles V both gave numerous works of art by Hans von Reutlingen.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] Continuing the tradition, objects continued to be donated until the present, each indicative of the period of its gifting, with the last documented gift being a chalice from 1960 made by Ewald Mataré.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] The Aachen Rathaus, (English: Aachen City Hall or Aachen Town Hall) dated from 1330, lies between two central squares, the *Markt* (marketplace) and the *Katschhof* (between city hall and cathedral).
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] The coronation hall is on the first floor of the building.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] Inside one can find five frescoes by the Aachen artist Alfred Rethel which show legendary scenes from the life of Charlemagne, as well as Charlemagne's signature.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] Also, precious replicas of the Imperial Regalia are kept here.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] Since 2009, the city hall has been a station on the *Route Charlemagne*, a tour programme by which historical sights of Aachen are presented to visitors.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] At the city hall, a museum exhibition explains the history and art of the building and gives a sense of the historical coronation banquets that took place there.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] A portrait of Napoleon from 1807 by Louis-André-Gabriel Bouchet and one of his wife Joséphine from 1805 by Robert Lefèvre are viewable as part of the tour.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] As before, the city hall is the seat of the mayor of Aachen and of the city council, and annually the Charlemagne Prize is awarded there.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] The *Grashaus*, a late medieval house at the *Fischmarkt*, is one of the oldest non-religious buildings in central Aachen.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] It hosted the city archive, and before that, the Grashaus was the city hall until the present building took over this function.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] The *Elisenbrunnen* is one of the most famous sights of Aachen.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] It is a neo-classical hall covering one of the city's famous fountains.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] It is just a minute away from the cathedral.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] Just a few steps in a south-easterly direction lies the 19th-century theatre.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] Also of note are two remaining city gates, the *Ponttor* (Pont gate), 800 metres (1⁄2 mile) northwest of the cathedral, and the *Marschiertor* (marching gate), close to the central railway station.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] There are also a few parts of both medieval city walls left, most of them integrated into more recent buildings, but some others still visible.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] There are even five towers left, some of which are used for housing.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] Michael's Church, Aachen was built as a church of the Aachen Jesuit Collegium in 1628.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] It is attributed to the Rhine mannerism, and a sample of a local Renaissance architecture.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] The rich façade remained unfinished until 1891, when the architect Peter Friedrich Peters added to it.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] The church is a Greek Orthodox church today, but the building is used also for concerts because of its good acoustics.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] The synagogue in Aachen, which was destroyed on the Night of Broken Glass (Kristallnacht), 9 November 1938, was reinaugurated on 18 May 1995.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] One of the contributors to the reconstructions of the synagogue was Jürgen Linden, the Lord Mayor of Aachen from 1989 to 2009.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] There are numerous other notable churches and monasteries, a few remarkable 17th- and 18th-century buildings in the particular Baroque style typical of the region, a synagogue, a collection of statues and monuments, park areas, cemeteries, among others.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] Among the museums in the town are the Suermondt-Ludwig Museum, which has a fine sculpture collection and the Aachen Museum of the International Press, which is dedicated to newspapers from the 16th century to the present.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] The area's industrial history is reflected in dozens of 19th- and early 20th-century manufacturing sites in the city.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] Aachen is the administrative centre for the coal-mining industries in neighbouring places to the northeast.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] Products manufactured in Aachen include electrical goods, fine woolen textiles, foodstuffs (chocolate and candy), glass, machinery, rubber products, furniture, metal products.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] Also in and around Aachen chemicals, plastics, cosmetics, and needles and pins are produced.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] Though once a major player in Aachen's economy, today glassware and textile production make up only 10% of total manufacturing jobs in the city.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] There have been a number of spin-offs from the university's IT technology department.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] In June 2010, Achim Kampker, together with Günther Schuh, founded a small company to develop electric powered light utility vehicles; in August 2014, it was renamed StreetScooter GmbH.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] This started as a privately organised research initiative at the RWTH Aachen University, before becoming the independent company in Aachen.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] Kampker was also the founder and chairman of the European Network for Affordable and Sustainable Electromobility.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] In May 2014, the company announced that the city of Aachen, the city council Aachen and the savings bank Aachen had ordered electric vehicles from the company.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] In late 2014, approximately 70 employees were manufacturing 200 vehicles annually in the premises of the Waggonfabrik Talbot, the former Talbot/Bombardier plant in Aachen.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] In December 2014 DHL Group purchased the StreetScooter company from Günther, operating it as a wholly owned subsidiary.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] In 2015, Günther founded a new electric vehicle company, e.GO Mobile, which started producing the e.GO Life electric passenger car and other vehicles in April 2019.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] By April 2016, StreetScooter announced that it would produce 2000 of its electric vans, branded the Work, in Aachen by the end of the year, and would be scaling up to manufacture approximately 10,000 Works annually, starting in 2017, also in Aachen.
[src:aachen/aachen-p01] At the time, this target would make it the largest electric light utility vehicle manufacturer in Europe, surpassing Renault's smaller Kangoo Z.E.
[src:aachen/aachen-p02] RWTH Aachen University, established as Polytechnicum in 1870, is one of Germany's Universities of Excellence with strong emphasis on technological research, especially for electrical and mechanical engineering, computer sciences, physics, and chemistry.
[src:aachen/aachen-p02] The university clinic attached to the RWTH, the Klinikum Aachen, is the biggest single-building hospital in Europe.
[src:aachen/aachen-p02] Over time, a host of software and computer industries have developed around the university.
[src:aachen/aachen-p02] It also maintains a botanical garden (the Botanischer Garten Aachen).
[src:aachen/aachen-p02] FH Aachen, Aachen University of Applied Sciences (AcUAS) was founded in 1971.
[src:aachen/aachen-p02] The AcUAS offers a classic engineering education in professions such as mechatronics, construction engineering, mechanical engineering or electrical engineering.
[src:aachen/aachen-p02] German and international students are educated in more than 20 international or foreign-oriented programmes and can acquire German as well as international degrees (Bachelor/Master) or *Doppelabschlüsse* (double degrees).
[src:aachen/aachen-p02] Foreign students account for more than 21% of the student body.
[src:aachen/aachen-p02] The Katholische Hochschule Nordrhein-Westfalen – Abteilung Aachen (Catholic University of Applied Sciences Northrhine-Westphalia – Aachen department) offers its some 750 students a variety of degree programmes: social work, childhood education, nursing, and co-operative management.
[src:aachen/aachen-p02] It also has the only programme of study in Germany especially designed for mothers.
[src:aachen/aachen-p02] The Hochschule für Musik und Tanz Köln (Cologne University of Music) is one of the world's foremost performing arts schools and one of the largest music institutions for higher education in Europe with one of its three campuses in Aachen.
[src:aachen/aachen-p02] The Aachen campus substantially contributes to the Opera/Musical Theatre master's programme by collaborating with the Theater Aachen and the recently established musical theatre chair through the Rheinische Opernakademie.
[src:aachen/aachen-p02] The German Army's technical school *(Ausbildungszentrum Technik Landsysteme)* is located in Aachen.
[src:aachen/aachen-p02] The annual CHIO (short for the French term *Concours Hippique International Officiel*) is the biggest equestrian meeting of the world and among horsemen is considered to be as prestigious for equitation as the tournament of Wimbledon for tennis.
[src:aachen/aachen-p02] Aachen hosted the 2006 FEI World Equestrian Games.
[src:aachen/aachen-p02] The local football team Alemannia Aachen had a short run in Germany's first division, after its promotion in 2006.
[src:aachen/aachen-p02] However, the team could not sustain its status and is now back in the third division.
[src:aachen/aachen-p02] The stadium "Tivoli", opened in 1928, served as the venue for the team's home games and was well known for its incomparable atmosphere throughout the whole of the second division.
[src:aachen/aachen-p02] Before the old stadium's demolition in 2011, it was used by amateurs, whilst the Bundesliga Club held its games in the new stadium "Neuer Tivoli" – meaning New Tivoli—a couple of metres down the road.
[src:aachen/aachen-p02] The building work for the stadium which has a capacity of 32,960, began in May 2008 and was completed by the beginning of 2009.
[src:aachen/aachen-p02] The Ladies in Black women's volleyball team (part of the "PTSV Aachen" sports club since 2013) has played in the first German volleyball league (DVL) since 2008.
[src:aachen/aachen-p02] In June 2022, the local basketball club BG Aachen e.V. was promoted to the 1st regional league.
[src:aachen/aachen-p02] Aachen's railway station, the Hauptbahnhof (Central Station), was constructed in 1841 for the Cologne–Aachen railway line.
[src:aachen/aachen-p02] In 1905, it was moved closer to the city centre.
[src:aachen/aachen-p02] It serves main lines to Cologne, Mönchengladbach and Liège as well as branch lines to Heerlen, Alsdorf, Stolberg and Eschweiler.
[src:aachen/aachen-p02] ICE high speed trains from Brussels via Cologne to Frankfurt am Main and Eurostar trains from Paris to Cologne also stop at Aachen Central Station.
[src:aachen/aachen-p02] Four RE lines and two RB lines connect Aachen with the Ruhrgebiet, Mönchengladbach, Spa (Belgium), Düsseldorf and the Siegerland.
[src:aachen/aachen-p02] The *Euregiobahn*, a regional railway system, reaches several minor cities in the Aachen region.
[src:aachen/aachen-p02] There are four smaller stations in Aachen: *Aachen West*, *Aachen Schanz*, *Aachen-Rothe Erde* and *Eilendorf*.
[src:aachen/aachen-p02] Aachen West has gained in importance with the expansion of RWTH Aachen University.
[src:aachen/aachen-p02] There are two stations for intercity bus services in Aachen: Aachen West station, in the north-west of the city, and Aachen Wilmersdorfer Straße, in the north-east.
[src:aachen/aachen-p02] The first horse tram line in Aachen opened in December 1880.
[src:aachen/aachen-p02] After electrification in 1895, it attained a maximum length of 213.5 kilometres (132+5⁄8 miles) in 1915, thus becoming the fourth-longest tram network in Germany.
[src:aachen/aachen-p02] Many tram lines extended to the surrounding towns of Herzogenrath, Stolberg, Alsdorf as well as the Belgian and Dutch communes of Vaals, Kelmis (then *Altenberg*) and Eupen.
[src:aachen/aachen-p02] The Aachen tram system was linked with the Belgian national interurban tram system.
[src:aachen/aachen-p02] Like many tram systems in Western Europe, the Aachen tram suffered from poorly maintained infrastructure and was so deemed unnecessary and disrupting for car drivers by local politics.
[src:aachen/aachen-p02] On 28 September 1974, the last line 15 (Vaals–Brand) operated for one last day and was then replaced by buses.
[src:aachen/aachen-p02] A proposal to reinstate a tram/light rail system under the name *Campusbahn* was dropped after a referendum.
[src:aachen/aachen-p02] Today, the ASEAG (*Aachener Straßenbahn und Energieversorgungs-AG*, literally "Aachen Tram and Power Supply Company") operates a 1,240.8-kilometre-long (771 mi) bus network with 68 bus routes.
[src:aachen/aachen-p02] Because of the location at the border, many bus routes extend to Belgium and the Netherlands.
[src:aachen/aachen-p02] Lines 14 to Eupen, Belgium and 44 to Heerlen, Netherlands are jointly operated with Transport en Commun and Veolia Transport Nederland, respectively.
[src:aachen/aachen-p02] ASEAG is one of the main participants in the Aachener Verkehrsverbund (AVV), a tariff association in the region.
[src:aachen/aachen-p02] Along with ASEAG, city bus routes of Aachen are served by private contractors such as Sadar, Taeter, Schlömer, or DB Regio Bus.
[src:aachen/aachen-p02] Line 350, which runs from Maastricht, also enters Aachen.
[src:aachen/aachen-p02] Aachen is connected to the Autobahn A4 (west-east), A44 (north-south) and A544 (a smaller motorway from the A4 to the *Europaplatz* near the city centre).
[src:aachen/aachen-p02] There are plans to eliminate traffic jams at the Aachen road interchange.
[src:aachen/aachen-p02] Maastricht Aachen Airport (IATA: **MST**, ICAO: **EHBK**) is the main airport of Aachen and Maastricht.
[src:aachen/aachen-p02] It is located around 15 nautical miles (28 kilometres; 17 miles) northwest of Aachen.
[src:aachen/aachen-p02] There is a shuttle-service between Aachen and the airport.
[src:aachen/aachen-p02] However, the airport only offers limited European destinations.
[src:aachen/aachen-p02] The nearest major international airports are Cologne Bonn Airport, located 88 km (55 mi) east and Düsseldorf Airport, located 97.1 km (60 mi) northeast of Aachen.
[src:aachen/aachen-p02] Recreational aviation is served by the (formerly military) Aachen Merzbrück Airfield.
[src:aachen/aachen-p02] Since 1950, a committee of Aachen citizens annually awards the Charlemagne Prize (German: *Karlspreis*) to personalities of outstanding service to the unification of Europe.
[src:aachen/aachen-p02] It is traditionally awarded on Ascension Day at the City Hall.
[src:aachen/aachen-p02] In 2016, the Charlemagne Award was awarded to Pope Francis.
[src:aachen/aachen-p02] In 2004, Pope John Paul II's efforts to unite Europe were honoured with an "Extraordinary Charlemagne Medal", which was awarded for the only time ever.
[src:aachen/aachen-p02] Aix is the destination in Robert Browning's poem "How They Brought the Good News from Ghent to Aix", which was published in *Dramatic Romances and Lyrics*, 1845.
[src:aachen/aachen-p02] The poem is a first-person narrative told, in breathless galloping meter, by one of three riders; an urgent midnight errand to deliver "the news which alone could save Aix from her fate".
[src:aachen/aachen-rothe-erde-station] With the opening of the Haaren–Aachen-Rothe Erde railway on 31 December 1875, the station was also opened by the Aachen Industrial Railway Company (*Aachener Industriebahn*) under the name of *Rothe Erde*.
[src:aachen/aachen-rothe-erde-station] Especially after Adolph Kirdorf accelerated the expansion of the *Aachener Hütten-Aktien-Vereins Rothe Erde* (Aachen Iron Works-Rothe Erde Association), the station served initially as a transfer station to the tracks connecting here to various factories in Rothe Erde.
[src:aachen/aachen-rothe-erde-station] As the station was originally only used for freight, it was used for connections to the coal mines in neighbouring Belgium, the northern part of the Aachen district and the quarries in Stolberg.
[src:aachen/aachen-rothe-erde-station] Ten years after its opening, the Venn Railway (*Vennbahn*) was opened, connecting to Luxembourg via Monschau and St.
[src:aachen/aachen-rothe-erde-station] Vith, and the station was connected to the local ARBED steel works.
[src:aachen/aachen-rothe-erde-station] The new Aachen-Rothe Erde locomotive workshop was opened at the same time.
[src:aachen/aachen-rothe-erde-station] The station has served passengers since 1880.
[src:aachen/aachen-rothe-erde-station] The railway tracks were relaid about 100 metres closer to the town in 1892 to remove rail traffic from the level crossing on an increasingly important arterial road, today's Trierer Straße.
[src:aachen/aachen-rothe-erde-station] The line was built over lower ground, while retaining its original height, allowing a bridge to be built over the road.
[src:aachen/aachen-rothe-erde-station] At the beginning of the 20th century, the station was renamed *Aachen-Rothe Erde*.
[src:aachen/aachen-rothe-erde-station] The locomotive workshop was closed in 1932.
[src:aachen/aachen-rothe-erde-station] In the Second World War, the station was badly damaged and the bridge over Trierer Straße was blown up.
[src:aachen/aachen-rothe-erde-station] The Aachen–Cologne line was not reopened until 1946.
[src:aachen/aachen-rothe-erde-station] As a result, the handling of steel, coke and limestone was abandoned and the station became less important for the transfer of freight.
[src:aachen/aachen-rothe-erde-station] Only the connections to Aachen Nord station and the neighbouring Waggonfabrik Talbot rolling stock factory and the Aachen Philips factories on the Venn Railway remained in operation.
[src:aachen/aachen-rothe-erde-station] In contrast, Rothe Erde station continued to serve passengers on the Aachen–Cologne line.
[src:aachen/aachen-rothe-erde-station] In 2004, the freight shed were finally demolished and the now disused railway land was mostly levelled for the construction of the *Aachen Arkaden* shopping centre.
[src:aachen/aachen-rothe-erde-station] In 2007, the entire station was rebuilt during the commissioning of the Aachen electronic interlocking.
[src:aachen/aachen-rothe-erde-station] The old freight and storage sidings were greatly scaled back.
[src:aachen/aachen-rothe-erde-station] Prior to the remodelling, the station had two mechanical signal boxes, one of which controlled the semaphore signals and points for passenger and freight operations at the station.
[src:aachen/aachen-rothe-erde-station] Another signal box called *Rr* was demolished in preparation for the construction of the Aachen Arkaden shopping centre in 2004.
[src:aachen/aachen-rothe-erde-station] Meanwhile, the station was equipped with Ks-signals, which are controlled remotely from the Duisburg electronic signalling centre.
[src:aachen/aachen-rothe-erde-station] The island platform was built from scratch and has a height of 76 cm (30 in) above the top of the rail.
[src:aachen/aachen-rothe-erde-station] The station also received a second access route on the eastern side with a lift for barrier-free access to the platform.
[src:aachen/aachen-rothe-erde-station] In the period from January 2007 until the opening on 9 October 2008 a large part of the former site of the former freight yard was demolished and replaced by the Aachen Arkaden, an office complex and shopping centre with 16,000 m2 (170,000 sq ft) of retail space.
[src:aachen/aachen-rothe-erde-station] It was built in a functional contemporary architectural style of minimalism with atriums with transparent glass roofs.
[src:aachen/aachen-rothe-erde-station] It has traditional arcades, a tower on six stilts and shops.
[src:aachen/aachen-rothe-erde-station] Part of the old freight yard is now used as sidings for the rolling stock and the railcars of Euregiobahn, which can be refuelled there.
[src:aachen/aachen-rothe-erde-station] Currently Aachen-Rothe Erde is served by the NRW-Express, Rhein-Sieg-Express and Euregiobahn.
[src:aachen/aachen-rothe-erde-station] In addition, the station is served at night by S-Bahn line S19, which runs to Aachen or Troisdorf.
